translate:
Deeply locked in the Leiman banquet, talents are displayed;
Watching dances and songs, passing cups in rotation.
Golden golden ibises sleep at the banquet table;
Red brocade roses cast their shadows in the candlelight.
The pleasant breeze blows on the Ji Ling mountains;
The remaining moon of Jinghu Lake shines on the tower.
The young scholar sits at the end of the seat, frequently leaning forward;
Fearful of the drawing of the bugle call on the city wall.

Verdant clouds intertwine, thin and twisted, through the ages; 
Bearing the sound of rain and wind for hundreds of springs. 
Deeply curled like a green fan, its tails swaying in the breeze; 
Old bark stretched out like black dragon scales, revealing its age. 
Only cold hues accumulate to inspire musical passion; 
Leaving autumn's sounds untouched by worldly dust. 
Time flows like waves, while events are but dreams; 
Who will remain, after all, to cherish this verdant sight?

Curved ponds with vibrant colors, where fish leap and swim,
Branch-shrouded paths, fresh waves rippling through the screen.
In this place, there is no better scene to be found;
Elsewhere, spring may not truly be spring.
Golden signs mark the path of immortal beings, as they gather for merriment;
Silver saddles, young nobles lose themselves in flowery dust.
Come back next year in February, and bask in the spring breeze;
Together, we'll embrace the season, and partake of its charm.

Fond of victory, I meet you to part;
Thinking of harmony, the grass and distant smoke entwine.
In the fragrance of small plums, yellow warblers sing;
Beneath the willows, white horses neigh.
The spring leads beautiful women to sing their songs;
The wind pulls the banners of wine for young nobles low.
Had I known this would affect my life,
I would have regretted not living in Yuexi last year.

In the end, the path to those I miss leads to the sea and clouds;
Seeking solitude, I hide in deep grass behind an isolated door.
As everything fades away, my dreams as a casual traveler subside;
A year has passed, leaving only emptiness on the young man's head.
The mountain frogs sing slowly, their song drifting from the shelves;
Wild geese from the Huai River come by often, but don't go up the stairs.
Recently, there is new wine in my neighbor's home;
With poetry companions, we linger and enjoy the moment.

In a hundred years, there are only a hundred clear springs;
This year, we avoid the soldiers again in disarray.
Who lights the fireworks and breaks the cold food ban?
Where are the beautiful people dressed in brocades?
The fields of grain and hemp are abandoned, creating a border atmosphere;
The sound of war rises from the cold spring vegetation.
The endless flying cranes pass through the heavens;
Since ancient times, it has been the city of Wu.

In middle age, with experience comes wisdom;
To learn from one's mistakes is not a sin.
Hastening to avoid the youthful and carefree,
One avoids the filth and does not respond.
With a sigh of relief, one is content;
One's plans are well-thought-out and complete.
A little effort erases the heavy guilt;
The slight humiliation is better than deep despair.
One knows that to be at the bottom is safe;
To be at the top brings no companions.
Each person has their own goals in life;
Brave or cowardly, they follow what they choose.

In the deserted garden with short walls, there's no neighbor for miles around; 
The fiery red peach blossoms illuminate the earth in spring. 
Sitting for a long time, I enjoy the gentle breeze and let my sleeves rest; 
At night, the light rain has soaked my silk scarf. 
I dare to expect a friendly glance from others, like whispers that stir my red lips; 
All day long, I have no thoughts of my hometown, so why should I see a person from Qin?

The elm and willow trees are sparse, the hot weather begins to subside;
The golden merchant's fire flows westward, frequently lying down.
Dusty clothes at the end of the year, because of my lowly position;
In the deeper rain, the bamboo mat cools my back in the autumn breeze.
What's the point in talking about the past, so sad and cold?
I'm lazy in writing letters, I can't even repair them.
I only wish to wait for the moon to rise under the high walnut tree;
I'll go to the eastern bed and visit Hui Hou again.

As the birds sing and the bees fly, the days grow longer;
Travelers' emotions, regretful thoughts, and reflection.
In the serene temple, one's heart is at peace;
Aloof from worldly affairs, one faces a wall.
In the second month, the mist and smoke veil the willow trees;
Along the busy streets, the wind and soil carry the fragrance of flowers.
The wise and elevated person banishes sorrow and loneliness;
Try to lean on the railing, but don't let your heart break.

Planted secretly, no one knows its fragrance;
Hidden charm, only held in silence.
Without a noble's appreciation, it's not yet a loss;
It's still the national fragrance, despite the decline.
Dewdrops wet the long grass, spring winds arrive late;
Incomparable to the weeds at the road, their fragrance spreads.

Clear [summer] curtains are opened, releasing a unique fragrance;
Gracious favor is deep, facing the dragon's royal emblem.
Flowers bloom normally in the secret cave;
Sunlight grows particularly long in the urn.
Sitting for a long time, suddenly suspecting an incursion into the Big Dipper;
Returning home, fearing the emergence of moulton grass in the sea.
Now we laugh coldly at Eastern Han's Dongfang Shuo;
Only using humor to serve the emperor.

Spring shade over the land, moistening the soil; 
Biting cold in spring, gentle wind brings harmony. 
Indulging in leisure, mocking those who compete; 
Drunkenly singing off-key, fisherman and woodcutter's song. 
Poetry pondered, doubtful if it can progress; 
Political ambition wanes, leaving less to do. 
Drunken enthusiasm still remains, but alas, 
A thousand silver strands of hair have turned white.
